---
description: User-visible copy must never promise or reference future releases
alwaysApply: true
---

# No “future version” product copy

When writing **operator-facing** strings in Guardian (SwiftUI `Text`, `.help`,
tooltips, alerts, empty states, button labels, accessibility labels, onboarding,
plugin UI, etc.):

- **Do not** mention “a future build”, “in a future version”, “coming soon”,
  “not yet — will …”, “for now”, “temporarily until we ship …”, or any wording
  that frames the **current** app as an incomplete preview of something else.
- Write as if **this build is the product**: describe **what is true right now**
  (what is locked, disabled, unavailable, or not supported) without teasing
  roadmap or release timing.

**OK:** “Arm preflight stays disabled until this Mission Control run ends.”

**Not OK:** “Overrides will arrive in a future build.”

## Exceptions

- **Internal** diagnostics (`notImplemented` command details, logs, developer
  comments, `ToDo/TODO.md`, tracker markdown) may still note wiring gaps for
  contributors — not as customer-facing chrome.
- **Version numbers** in About / settings (“Guardian 1.2.3”) are not roadmap
  copy.

## When a surface is stubbed

Prefer neutral present tense: **“Unavailable.”**, **“No options in this group.”**,
or **hide** the element from accessibility (`accessibilityHidden(true)`) when
it is purely layout chrome with no behavior — do not use “Coming soon” as
placeholder UI copy.
